<div id="review_3047686020" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3047686020" />
    <a title="Matt McBride" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/89844312-matt-mcbride"><img alt="Matt McBride" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1543278653p2/89844312.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3047686020?book_show_action=true">Nov 13, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matt McBride" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matt McBride" href="/user/show/89844312-matt-mcbride">Matt McBride</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780887480218" href="/book/show/150320.Thomas_and_Beulah">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3047686020" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6140584394767142962">Dove&apos;s ability to both reveal while also allowing for the ways memory make things opaque floors me. Thomas and Beulah is a staggering work of empathy. Each poem is a glimpse in a life that is quickly enveloped by the radical inability to know another&apos;s consciousness (which is mimetic of the unsuitability of history itself). Dove both gives us the lives of her grandparents, while also protecting the parts of them they never shared. </span>
  <span id="freeText6140584394767142962" style="display:none">Dove's ability to both reveal while also allowing for the ways memory make things opaque floors me. Thomas and Beulah is a staggering work of empathy. Each poem is a glimpse in a life that is quickly enveloped by the radical inability to know another's consciousness (which is mimetic of the unsuitability of history itself). Dove both gives us the lives of her grandparents, while also protecting the parts of them they never shared. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6140584394767142962" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


